Thank you for listening to my #Oscars rant. Also, please forgive any and all spelling/grammar errors that were made in my haste to vent all my feelings. #Oscars2019 #OscarNoms #AcademyAwards
You can think I’m crazy or that I’m totally wrong in all this. But that’s just my opinion and it’s something that I’m passionate about. I think the Oscars mean something, at least the should.
It’s what the Oscar is supposed to represent, excellence in one’s craft, and what a movie like Bohemian Rhapsody could do to tarnish that meaning. That’s all.
So that’s my issue with this whole Bohemian Rhapsody thing. It’s not because A Star is Born lost (like a lot of people think). It’s the principle of the matter.
The answer is, there really is none. If any movie that can win a PCA can win an Oscar, then the Oscar has no meaning anymore.

If a big blockbuster movie like Bohemian Rhapsody can go against these character pieces for an Academy Award and win (we don’t know yet, but I think it has a chance if the other award shows show anything), then what is the point of the Oscars anymore?

Now, the Academy has voted to have a category just for blockbusters, but they voted it down. And while I get that, I don’t think they should let these blockbusters compete against the types of films that the Academy has always represented.

Now with the Golden Globes and Oscars, these are typically shows giving awards to the character/story driven films with the lower budgets because that is what these award shows have typically been there for.
And in that realm of things, that’s actually a pretty big honor because those movies are made for the people, so if the people choose you...

With these different calibers of movies, there are different calibers of award shows to correlate with them. In the world of Blockbusters, the best awards you can get is mainly the People’s Choice Awards.

These films have more minimalistic production designs and smaller casts, but that’s because their stories are character driven and that’s the focus. They can have bigger production designs too, but that’s not what these films are about.

Smaller budget films/Indies on the other hand are made for different reasons. They are more niche films and are pointed towards certain people, and more often that not those people are cinephiles or film critics.

Now, don’t get me wrong. Some blockbuster films actually have pretty decent storylines and character development, but it’s not as often within these films. They’re just supposed to be fun and to escape for a couple hours.

Movies/Blockbusters such as Bohemian Rhapsody are created for a certain reason, the people. They focus mainly on production design and big casts to draw in as many people to the theater as possible. Because of this, there typically isn’t as much focus on character or story.
I don’t even want to talk about the story of Bohemian Rhapsody and the issues that lie within, I just want to focus on film/story in general.

So apparently there are still people out there who actually think that Bohemian Rhapsody is the beat choice for Best Picture at the Oscars, and honestly I don’t know what to say. Actually, I do. So sit down, relax and welcome to my Ted Talk.

I am just so blessed to have her in my life, but my life will feel a little more empty now that she's not here in Vancouver with me.
